[Event "Immortal Game"]
[Site "London"]
[Date "1851.06.21"]
[White "Adolf Anderssen"]
[Black "Lionel Kieseritzky"]
[Result "1-0"]

1. e4 e5 2. f4 {The King's Gambit — Anderssen's favourite opening.} exf4 3. Bc4 Qh4+ 4. Kf1 b5?! {The Bryan Countergambit. Aggressive but dubious.} (4... Nf6 {The modern refutation.} 5. Nf3 Qh5) (4... d5 {Solid central counter.} 5. Bxd5 Nf6) 5. Bxb5 Nf6 6. Nf3 Qh6 7. d3 Nh5 8. Nh4 Qg5 9. Nf5 c6 10. g4 {Boldly chasing the knight away, ignoring material.} Nf6 11. Rg1! {Preparing the sacrifice. White ignores conventional development.} cxb5 12. h4! Qg6 13. h5 Qg5 14. Qf3 Ng8 15. Bxf4 Qf6 16. Nc3 Bc5 17. Nd5 {Threatening Nxf6+ and Bxc7.} Qxb2 18. Bd6! {A spectacular quiet move — threatening Nxg7# and blocking the d-file.} (18. Nxg7+? Kd8 {And Black escapes.}) Bxd6? (18... Qxa1+ 19. Ke2 Qb2 {Was the best try, but White still has a strong attack.} 20. Nxg7+ Kd8 21. Bc7+! Ke8 22. Nb6) 19. Nxg7+ Kd8 20. Qf6+! {The final combination begins.} Nxf6 21. Be7# {Checkmate! One of the most beautiful games ever played.} 1-0
